<h2>Arkansas Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Arkansas offers several attractive financial incentives for solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems, making these upgrades more affordable for homeowners throughout the state. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the most significant incentive, allowing homeowners to deduct 30% of their total solar installation costs from their federal income taxes. This credit applies to all system components, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor, with no cap on the credit amount. The 30% credit rate is available through 2032, after which it will step down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034.</p>

<p>At the state level, Arkansas provides a property tax exemption for renewable energy systems, including solar panels and geothermal heat pumps. This exemption ensures that adding solar panels or other qualifying renewable energy equipment to a home will not increase the property's assessed value for taxation purposes, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime. The exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and covers the full value of the renewable energy system addition.</p>

<p>Entergy Arkansas offers several rebate programs for energy-efficient equipment through their Solutions for Business and Solutions for Your Home programs. Residential customers can receive rebates of \$50-100 per ton for high-efficiency heat pumps and air conditioning systems that meet specific SEER and HSPF requirements. Additional rebates are available for smart thermostats (\$50-75), duct sealing services (\$200-400), and comprehensive home energy audits. While Entergy Arkansas does not currently offer direct solar rebates, their net metering program allows solar customers to receive retail rate credit for excess electricity fed back into the grid, maximizing the value of solar production.</p>

<p>Local utility cooperatives throughout Arkansas may offer additional rebate programs for their members. Many electric cooperatives provide rebates for heat pump installations, energy-efficient appliances, and weatherization improvements. Some cooperatives also offer special time-of-use rate structures that can benefit solar panel owners by providing higher compensation rates during peak demand periods when solar production is typically at its highest.</p>

